# Persona UX Reviewer — Cursor Project Rules

## Project Overview
This is a Next.js 14+ (App Router) TypeScript application that:
1. Takes a target market description + app URL as input
2. Uses Gemini AI (Google) to generate a user persona
3. Uses Stagehand (Browserbase) to navigate the app as that persona
4. Uses Gemini AI with vision to analyze screenshots and produce a UX report

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 14+ with App Router and TypeScript
- Google Gemini API (@google/generative-ai SDK) for persona generation and vision-based analysis
- Stagehand (@browserbasehq/stagehand) for AI-native browser automation
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui for the frontend
- Deployed on Vercel + Browserbase Cloud

## Key Architecture Rules
- All LLM calls go through lib/gemini.ts using the @google/generative-ai SDK
- Use Gemini 2.5 Pro for analysis tasks (multimodal) and Gemini 2.0 Flash for simple/fast tasks
- All browser automation goes through lib/browser.ts using Stagehand
- The API route at app/api/review/route.ts orchestrates the full pipeline
- Prompts are centralized in lib/prompts.ts
- Types are centralized in lib/types.ts

## Gemini-Specific Rules
- Use GoogleGenerativeAI class from @google/generative-ai
- For vision tasks, pass images as inline_data with base64 encoding and mimeType
- Use generationConfig for temperature, topP, maxOutputTokens
- Use responseMimeType: "application/json" for structured JSON output
- Handle rate limits with exponential backoff

## Stagehand-Specific Rules
- Use act() for interactions: clicking, typing, scrolling
- Use observe() to find elements on the page
- Use extract() to pull structured data from the page
- Always take screenshots after key navigation steps
- Set reasonable timeouts (30s default)
- Handle navigation errors gracefully

## Code Style
- Use async/await everywhere (no raw Promises)
- Use Zod for runtime validation of LLM outputs
- Centralize error handling in the API route
- Use server actions or API routes for all backend logic
- Never expose API keys to the client
